==English==
===Etymology===
From Old French ''dragon'' (French ''dragon''), from Latinized {{Gr.}} [[draco]], from 
[[Ancient Greek]] '''[[δράκων]]''' (''drakon'') "a serpent of huge size, a python, a dragon", from '''[[δρακείν]]''' (''drakein'') aor. inf. act. of '''[[δέρκομαι]]''' (''derkomai'') "to see clearly".

===Pronunciation===
* {{AHD|drăg'ən}}
* {{IPA|/ˈdrægən/}}
* {{SAMPA|/"dr{g@n/}}
* Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-ægən|-ægən]]

===Noun===
[[Category:Greek root δερκ]]
[[Category:Mythological creatures]]
{{en-noun}}



# A gigantic [[mythical]] [[beast]], commonly [[reptilian]] with leathery [[wings]], [[lion]]-like [[claws]], scaly skin and a serpent-like [[tail]], often with [[fiery]] breath.
# (Western) An enormous fire-breathing lizard-like animal with a large pair of foldable bat-style wings on its back, sharp claws and teeth, slit-like eye pupils, crescent-shaped nostrils, and a long serpentine tail (often used in wrapping or constricting prey). Known for its ferocious anger (draconian = strict, violent).
# (Eastern) A large snake-like lizard with the eyes of a hare, the horns of a stag, and the claws of a tiger; known for its benevolent behavior in ancient Oriental mythology.
# A [[reptile]], especially a [[Komodo dragon]].
# A possible early word for a [[dinosaur]].
# {{pejorative}} An [[unpleasant]] [[woman]]; a [[harridan]].
#:''She's a bit of a '''dragon'''.''

